{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-template-js","path":"/posts/using-vim-tabs","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"id":"907cb88e-299e-5fda-870a-6b10e4f2b727","html":"<p>I started using tabs just recently in <code class=\"language-text\">vim</code> and found it pretty useful.<br>\nHere are a couple of tips on how to create, open and navigate tabs in my favorite editor.</p>\n<h1 id=\"create\"><a href=\"#create\" aria-label=\"create permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Create</h1>\n<p><img src=\"/a10bca9a431aec3d5753074f5e4be625/vim-tabs-newfile.gif\" alt=\"Create files in vim\"></p>\n<p>There are many ways to create a new file on the command line.  </p>\n<p>In <code class=\"language-text\">vim</code>, you can start to create a new file using tabs with the following:</p>\n<p>Type <code class=\"language-text\">:tabnew</code> and then hit <code class=\"language-text\">ENTER</code></p>\n<p>On my Mac, this drops me into the editor in <em>insert</em> mode.<br>\nYou may need to enter <em>insert</em> mode manually (i.e. hit <code class=\"language-text\">i</code>).</p>\n<p>Type away to your heart’s content!</p>\n<p>To write the file:\nHit <code class=\"language-text\">ESC</code>\nType <code class=\"language-text\">:w file_name</code> and then enter. </p>\n<h1 id=\"open\"><a href=\"#open\" aria-label=\"open permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Open</h1>\n<p><img src=\"/fa18351de389b1d21a6f14c6584a53ef/vim-tabs-editfile.gif\" alt=\"Edit files in vim\"></p>\n<p>Open an existing file using <code class=\"language-text\">:tabe name_of_file</code>.</p>\n<p>Be mindful of your spelling because if <code class=\"language-text\">name_of_file</code> doesn’t exist, <code class=\"language-text\">vim</code> will open a tab with an empty buffer as though you were trying to create a new file.   </p>\n<h1 id=\"navigate\"><a href=\"#navigate\" aria-label=\"navigate permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Navigate</h1>\n<p><img src=\"/43c7bfc52db9d5bf0fb619619ee147fb/vim-tabs-gotabs.gif\" alt=\"Navigate in vim\"></p>\n<p>In <em>command</em> mode (hit <code class=\"language-text\">ESC</code>):</p>\n<p>Navigate forward between tabs with <code class=\"language-text\">gt</code>.<br>\nNavigate back using <code class=\"language-text\">gT</code>.    </p>","fields":{"slug":"/posts/using-vim-tabs","tagSlugs":null},"frontmatter":{"date":"2019-11-15","description":"I started using tabs just recently in vim and found it pretty useful.","tags":null,"title":"How to Use Tabs in vim","socialImage":null}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/posts/using-vim-tabs"}}}